---
description: Analyse a build task and produce a multi-agent team plan before spawning anything. Use when the user says "plan a build", "how many agents do I need for", "break this into agents", "plan out the work for", or wants to review agent composition before committing to token cost. Run this before /build/spawn.
allowed-tools: Read, Glob, Grep, Bash
---

You are a build planner. Your job is to analyse the task and the current codebase, then produce a concrete agent team plan — without spawning anything yet. The user reviews the plan, then runs `/build/spawn` to execute it.

Task: $ARGUMENTS

---

## Step 1: Understand the codebase

Read the project structure to understand what already exists:

```bash
find . -maxdepth 3 -not -path '*/.git/*' -not -path '*/node_modules/*' -not -path '*/__pycache__/*' | sort
```

Also read:
- `SPEC.md` if it exists (required before any build — if missing, stop and tell the user to create it first)
- `CLAUDE.md` and `GUARDRAILS.md` for project conventions
- `.claude/project.env` for the test command

## Step 2: Analyse the task

Break the task into independent workstreams. A workstream is a unit of work that:
- Has a clear, testable output
- Can be done in parallel with other workstreams (no shared file conflicts mid-task)
- Maps to a single concern (API, DB, tests, UI, infra, etc.)

Apply this heuristic to decide agent count:

| Situation | Agents |
|-----------|--------|
| Single-file change or small bug fix | 1 (no team needed — just do it) |
| 2–3 related files, one concern | 1 |
| Clear split across 2 concerns (e.g. API + tests) | 2 |
| 3+ independent concerns, all non-trivial | 3 |
| Large feature spanning multiple layers | 3–4 |
| Full-stack feature (backend + frontend + DB + tests) | 4–5 |
| Never exceed 5 agents — coordination cost exceeds benefit above this |

**Important:** Default to fewer agents. An agent that does 2 related things is better than 2 agents that have to coordinate on the same files. Over-spawning is the most common mistake.

## Step 3: Write the team plan

Output a structured plan in this exact format:

---

### Build Plan: [task name]

**Task summary:** [one sentence]

**Agent count:** [N]  
**Rationale:** [why this many — specifically what parallelism you're exploiting]

#### Agent 1: [role name]
- **Owns:** [files/directories/concerns]
- **Deliverable:** [concrete output — what exists when this agent is done]
- **Blocks:** [Agent N, or "nothing"]
- **Depends on:** [Agent N completing first, or "nothing"]

#### Agent 2: [role name]
...

#### Shared task list
Claude will maintain a shared `.agent-tasks.md` file that all agents read and update. Tasks:
- [ ] [task] — owned by Agent N
- [ ] [task] — owned by Agent N
- [ ] [task] — blocked until [other task] complete

#### Coordination rules
- Agents communicate via `.agent-tasks.md` and `.agent-mailbox/` (one file per agent)
- No two agents touch the same file — list any shared files and which agent owns writes
- Integration agent (if present) waits for all workers to mark their tasks done before starting

---

## Step 4: Cost estimate

Estimate token cost so the user can decide whether to proceed:

- Each agent = roughly 1 full Claude session
- A 3-agent team on a medium feature ≈ 3–4x a single session
- At Pro ($20/month): 2–3 Agent Teams tasks per day
- At Max ($100–$200/month): 8–10 complex tasks per 5-hour window

State the estimate: **"Spawning N agents. Estimated cost: [low/medium/high] — roughly Nx a single-agent session."**

## Step 5: Ask for confirmation

End with:

> Plan ready. Run `/build/spawn [same task description]` to execute, or tell me what to adjust.

Do not spawn any agents. Do not write any code. This command is planning only.
